<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-12-15T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-12-15T23:00:00-05:00" n="527" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d527">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">723.2515/3244: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Moore</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-12-15T23:00:00-05:00">December 15, 1928—11
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 16—5:04
                            a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>143. Your 87, December 14, 6 p.m. Today I saw President Leguia. The
                            President agrees with you that the authorities of Chile would probably
                            find out about Colonel Moore’s visit and the reasons therefor. Since he
                            does not wish anyone to know what is in his mind, <pb facs="0858" n="722" xml:id="pg_722"/> and he has not even told one of his
                            Ministers, he has decided not to send Colonel Moore. I will keep you
                            informed of any later developments. President Leguia may send someone
                            else.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Moore</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>